      Beyond bloodbath
   =20
 =20

On Jan. 20, Bed Bath & Beyond Inc. had about  117.3 million shares of commo=
n stock outstanding; the stock closed that day at $3.35 per share. On March=
 27, it=C2=A0had about  428.1 million shares=C2=A0outstanding, at $0.7881 e=
ach. On April 10, it had  558.7 million shares outstanding, at $0.2961 each=
. Yesterday, April 23, when it   filed for bankruptcy, it had=C2=A0739,056,=
836 shares outstanding.
  [1]
=C2=A0The stock closed at $0.2935 on Friday.=C2=A0
So in the last two weeks, Bed Bath & Beyond has sold about 180 million shar=
es to retail investors, more shares than it had outstanding in January. The=
 stock averaged about $0.31 per share over those two weeks, meaning that th=
e company raised maybe $55 million, in those two weeks, as it has been slid=
ing into bankruptcy. Since January, Bed Bath & Beyond has sold about 622 mi=
llion shares, or almost 50 million shares a week, raising a few hundred mil=
lion dollars.=C2=A0
Here is Bed Bath=E2=80=99s  first-day declaration in the bankruptcy case, w=
hich describes what the company has been up to over the last few months. Th=
e points that I would highlight are:
=09In December 2022, =E2=80=9CBed Bath & Beyond triggered multiple events o=
f defaults under its financing facilities=E2=80=9D and began its slow move=
=C2=A0into bankruptcy.=09Also in December 2022, its financial advisers at L=
azard =E2=80=9Ccommenced a process to solicit interest in a going-concern s=
ale transaction that could be effectuated in chapter 11,=E2=80=9D that is, =
to find someone who was interested in buying the company out of bankruptcy =
and continuing to operate its business.=09They failed: By mid-January, =E2=
=80=9CLazard had engaged with approximately 60 potential investors to solic=
it interest in serving as a plan sponsor, acquiring some or all of the Debt=
ors=E2=80=99 assets or businesses, or providing postpetition financing,=E2=
=80=9D=C2=A0but =E2=80=9Cto date, the Company has been yet to identify an e=
xecutable transaction.=E2=80=9D=09So, as of mid-January, it seems that the =
company=E2=80=99s plan was to file for bankruptcy, close all its stores, li=
quidate its inventory and hand whatever cash was left to its creditors.=09B=
ut Bed Bath did have one thing going for it. It was =E2=80=9Cpart of the =
=E2=80=98meme-stock=E2=80=99 movement started and fueled on Reddit boards a=
nd social media websites,=E2=80=9D because it =E2=80=9Cchecked the two boxe=
s needed to become a meme-stock: (i) a troubled financial situation and (ii=
) nostalgia value.=E2=80=9D
  [2]

=09So someone had the bright idea of delaying things for a bit by selling t=
ons and tons of stock to Bed Bath=E2=80=99s retail shareholders at whatever=
=C2=A0prices they=E2=80=99d pay. =E2=80=9CCertain third-party investors exp=
ressed interest in providing the Debtors with substantial equity financing =
in light of the Company=E2=80=99s depressed share price and continued tradi=
ng volatility. More specifically, the Debtors were approached by Hudson Bay=
 Capital Management, LP=E2=80=9D about a weird stock deal that we   discuss=
ed in   January; this ended up   raising about $360 million. After the Huds=
on Bay deal ran its course =E2=80=94=C2=A0basically, after Hudson Bay and B=
ed Bath drove the stock price from above $3 to below $1 by pounding out abo=
ut 311 million shares to retail investors =E2=80=94=C2=A0Bed Bath and its b=
rokers at B. Riley Securities Inc. sold=C2=A0another=C2=A0311 million share=
s to retail investors, but at ever-declining prices, so they raised a lot l=
ess money. Still something, though.

It was not enough, though, and ultimately this weekend Bed Bath & Beyond fi=
led for=20
exactly the sort of bankruptcy it was contemplating in January: Close all t=
he stores, liquidate the inventory, hand whatever cash is left=C2=A0to the =
creditors. =E2=80=9CThe Debtors are committed to achieving the highest or o=
therwise best bid for some or all of the Debtors=E2=80=99 assets by marketi=
ng their assets pursuant to the Bidding Procedures, and, if necessary, cond=
ucting an auction for any of their assets,=E2=80=9D the company says, but i=
t has had like four months to find someone interested in buying the busines=
s, and if no one has shown up yet no one is going to. And: =E2=80=9CThe Deb=
tors estimate that the aggregate net sales proceeds from all Sales will be =
approximately $718 million,=E2=80=9D against=C2=A0about $1.8 billion of deb=
t to pay off.=C2=A0Nonetheless:
While the commencement of a full chain wind-down is necessitated by economi=
c realities, Bed Bath & Beyond has and will continue to market their busine=
sses as a going-concern, including the buybuy Baby business. Bed Bath & Bey=
ond has pulled off long shot transactions several times in the last six mon=
ths, so nobody should think Bed Bath & Beyond will not be able to do so aga=
in. To the contrary, Bed Bath & Beyond and its professionals will make ever=
y effort to salvage all or a portion of operations for the benefit of all s=
takeholders.
I said above that the few hundred million dollars that Bed Bath raised by s=
elling 622 million shares of stock=C2=A0since it started preparing for bank=
ruptcy =E2=80=9Cwas not enough=E2=80=9D to solve its problems, but it=E2=80=
=99s actually a bit worse than that. Bed Bath=E2=80=99s bankruptcy filing=
=C2=A0tells a story in which the company got into a bad place due to a comb=
ination of pandemic/supply-chain issues and its own management mistakes; in=
 particular, its former chief executive officer pushed private-label brands=
 instead of the well-known brands that its customers wanted. Bed Bath reali=
zed its mistakes and began correcting them =E2=80=94=C2=A0that CEO =E2=80=
=9Cwas excused on June 29, 2022=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0but that takes mone=
y; =E2=80=9Cthe Company needed real runway to turn around its inventory and=
 liquidity position.=E2=80=9D
But the story is=C2=A0not=C2=A0that it then went out and raised several hun=
dred million dollars to build up its inventory and make its business more a=
ttractive. No, the story is that it went out and raised several hundred mil=
lion dollars to hand directly=C2=A0to its creditors:

Unfortunately, under the terms of the Second Amended Credit Agreement, the =
Debtors were required to use the net proceeds from the initial closing of t=
he [Hudson Bay] Offering, along with the FILO Upsize, to repay outstanding =
revolving loans under the Debtors=E2=80=99 Prepetition ABL=C2=A0Facility, i=
ncluding repayment of the nearly $200 million overadvance. At this point th=
e Company=E2=80=99s sales had dropped 60% on a comparable store basis, resu=
