      Dual-class stock
   =20
 =20

Most investors would prefer not to have dual-class stock. If a company has =
two classes of common stock, one of which has a lot of votes and is held by=
 the founders and the other one of which has fewer votes and is sold to the=
 public, then that=E2=80=99s bad, for you, as a big public shareholder. If =
you=E2=80=99re buying 5% of a company you=E2=80=99d like to get 5% of the v=
otes, so that if you get dissatisfied with management you can push for chan=
ge and they=E2=80=99ll have to listen to you.
But it can be a little hard to=C2=A0insist=C2=A0on this preference. Most of=
 the time, if things work out well or even adequately, your voting rights j=
ust won=E2=80=99t matter very much. If some hot tech company is looking to =
go public with dual-class stock so that its visionary founder can keep cont=
rol forever, and you like the visionary founder, you will want to own the s=
tock even with no voting rights, and if you insist on voting rights, the vi=
sionary founder can say =E2=80=9Cwell I don=E2=80=99t need your money anywa=
y, lots of other people want to invest.=E2=80=9D There is a collective acti=
on problem: Most investors would=C2=A0like=C2=A0voting rights, but it=E2=80=
=99s not at the top of their list, so anyone who refuses to buy dual-class =
stock will end up missing out on a lot of hot deals.
This means that, if you are a visionary founder looking to go public, there=
=E2=80=99s not much downside to having dual-class stock. =E2=80=9CInvestors=
 won=E2=80=99t like it,=E2=80=9D your bankers will tell you, and you will a=
sk =E2=80=9Cwell how much less will they pay for the stock if it=E2=80=99s =
dual-class,=E2=80=9D and the bankers will be forced to reply =E2=80=9Cwell =
they=E2=80=99ll pay the same price but they=E2=80=99ll grumble about it to =
the press.=E2=80=9D Who cares? If there is no visible=C2=A0economic=C2=A0pe=
nalty for having dual-class stock, lots of founders will want it.
There is, however, at least one way for investors to act collectively to ad=
dress this problem. Sort of. Companies, and founders, want to be in stock=
=C2=A0indexes, because there is a lot of money there: Trillions of dollars =
are managed in indexed strategies, and trillions more are in funds that are=
 benchmarked to indexes and tend to invest in companies in indexes. So ther=
e=C2=A0is=C2=A0an economic penalty for companies that are not eligible for =
the indexes. And index eligibility rules are set by index providers like S&=
P Dow Jones Indices and FTSE Russell. Those companies can change their rule=
s if they want. Those companies=E2=80=99=C2=A0clients=C2=A0are investment m=
anagers who use their indexes. And the index eligibility rules are, to some=
 extent, a matter of customer service=C2=A0and=C2=A0marketing:=C2=A0Index r=
ules are not just about the abstract pursuit of truth (=E2=80=9CWhat does i=
t mean to be a large-cap company in Europe, the Middle East and Africa? How=
 do we make sure all of those companies are in our index?=E2=80=9D), but al=
so about providing a useful product for your customers (=E2=80=9CWhat list =
of large-cap EMEA companies do large-cap EMEA index fund managers feel like=
 they should invest in?=E2=80=9D).
And so if all the investment managers hate dual-class stock, they can quiet=
ly call up the index providers and say =E2=80=9Chey it would be helpful for=
 us if you ban dual-class stocks from the index, because then none of us co=
uld buy them and our collective action problem would be solved.=E2=80=9D
In 2017, Snap Inc.   went public by selling=C2=A0non-voting=C2=A0stock; onl=
y founders and insiders would get any votes at all. Investors complained, a=
nd also bought the stock, because they didn=E2=80=99t want to miss out on a=
 hot initial public offering. (It=E2=80=99s down more than 40% since its IP=
O, oops.) But then some index providers =E2=80=94=C2=A0FTSE Russell and   S=
&P Dow Jones =E2=80=94=C2=A0changed their rules to exclude or limit dual-cl=
ass stocks from many of their indexes. The investors had solved their colle=
ctive action problem; they had found a way to impose economic penalties on =
companies with dual-class stock.
It didn=E2=80=99t work. Companies kept going public with dual-class stock. =
They didn=E2=80=99t care=C2=A0that=C2=A0much about missing out on the index=
es; their founders were willing to pay the economic price to keep control. =
(In particular, companies don=E2=80=99t generally get added to the S&P 500=
=C2=A0the day they go public; a lot of index demand is not for shares in th=
e IPO but later on, meaning that it doesn=E2=80=99t directly affect the IPO=
 price.) This means that the investors=E2=80=99 solution ended up being=C2=
=A0bad=C2=A0for them: They credibly committed to not buying dual-class stoc=
k of hot companies, hot companies kept going public with dual-class stock, =
index funds couldn=E2=80=99t buy those stocks, and they were sad.=C2=A0
The solution was to give up. Last week  S&P Dow Jones announced that dual-c=
lass stocks are fine again: =E2=80=9CEffective April 17, 2023, all companie=
s with multiple share class structures will be considered eligible candidat=
es for addition to the S&P Composite 1500 and its component indices,=E2=80=
=9D including the S&P 500. Here=E2=80=99s a  Davis Polk & Wardwell LLP clie=
nt memo from last week:

In response to Snap Inc.=E2=80=99s IPO in which only non-voting shares were=
 offered to the public, the Council of Institutional Investors and others h=
ad lobbied the major index providers to bar non-voting shares from their in=
dices, arguing that absent this change, passive investors such as index fun=
ds would be forced to invest in non-voting shares that erode public company=
 governance. As a result, since July 31, 2017, S&P Dow Jones has excluded c=
ompanies with multiple share classes from the indices comprising the S&P Co=
mposite 1500.
The decision to revisit index eligibility criteria comes after a consultati=
on process that S&P Dow Jones ran with market participants from October to =
December 2022.

In 2017, investors noisily=C2=A0complained that they were being forced to b=
uy dual-class stocks, so S&P kicked the dual-class stocks out of the indexe=
s. In 2022, investors noisily complained that they were being forced=C2=A0n=
ot to buy dual-class stocks, so S&P let them back in.

