      Oil rigging
   =20
 =20

I loved Liam Vaughan=E2=80=99s and Lucia Kassai=E2=80=99s   Bloomberg Busin=
essweek story last week about corruption in Venezuelan oil auctions, in par=
t because it is two almost entirely separate stories of corruption. For sta=
rters, there are the Venezuelan oil auctions. Venezuela=E2=80=99s state oil=
 company, Petr=C3=B3leos de Venezuela SA, would sell various oil products i=
n auctions, and big oil trading firms would hire=C2=A0a consulting firm nam=
ed Helsinge, run by a guy=C2=A0named Francisco Morillo, to help them win th=
e auctions. The way he allegedly helped them win was (1) he bribed PDVSA in=
siders to tell him about the other bids, (2) he shared those bids with his =
clients, (3) the clients topped those bids by a penny and (4) they paid him=
 enough to cover the bribes with some profit for himself:

In one series of chats from March 14, 2006, Morillo, using the screen name =
George White, guided three prominent commodity traders=E2=80=94Maarraoui at=
 Vitol, Gustavo Gabaldon at Glencore and Maximiliano Poveda at Trafigura=E2=
=80=94through auctions for fuel oil and a product called vacuum gas oil, wh=
ich is used to make gasoline. At 9:51 a.m., nine minutes before the offers =
were due, Morillo shared details of the bids PDVSA had received for the vac=
uum gas oil=E2=80=94information PDVSA says is supposed to be confidential. =
Five minutes later he informed the three traders, via separate chats, of a =
late bid for the fuel oil.
The traders didn=E2=80=99t enter every auction, but when they did bid, the =
information Morillo had provided let them know at what price to do so. On M=
arch 20, 2006, after learning about offers from BP Plc and two other compan=
ies, Maarraoui placed a bid to buy gas oil at 0.8=C2=A2 per gallon more tha=
n the next-highest bidder. Two days later, Poveda won a liquefied petroleum=
 gas auction after being told about two rival offers and besting them by a =
cent.
These conversations, a handful among thousands, demonstrate how valuable He=
lsinge=E2=80=99s service was to its customers=E2=80=94and how potentially d=
evastating it was to the Venezuelan people. If Morillo=E2=80=99s clients ha=
d been forced to enter the market blind, they likely would have placed some=
 bids at $5 or $10 per metric ton higher than they needed to, as the chats =
show their competitors did. Instead the traders were able to win auctions t=
hey entered by a dollar or less, saving as much as $1.5 million on a typica=
l 150,000-ton cargo. According to the Boies complaint, they=E2=80=99d pay H=
elsinge about $300,000 on a shipment of that size. PDVSA declined to provid=
e data to Businessweek on the outcome of its auctions, or to comment for th=
is story, but given that the company conducted dozens of auctions each mont=
h as buyer and seller, and that Helsinge was in business for 15 years, it=
=E2=80=99s conceivable Venezuela lost out on several billion this way.

Also, if you keep doing this, eventually you=E2=80=99re going to drive ever=
yone=C2=A0else=C2=A0out of the auctions, further depressing prices:
Traders from two oil companies told Businessweek that they=E2=80=99d stoppe=
d participating in PDVSA=E2=80=99s auctions because they were sick of losin=
g to the same players. =E2=80=9CPutting together an offer takes time. You n=
eed to figure out the economics, freight, insurance, the hedge, then submit=
 to your compliance, get signatures from God knows who before you=E2=80=99r=
e able to submit a number,=E2=80=9D says one of the individuals, who asked =
not to be identified. =E2=80=9CAfter a while we just gave up. It became cle=
ar to us that something funny was happening.=E2=80=9D
This part of the story includes some classics of the =E2=80=9Cdon=E2=80=99t=
 put it in writing=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cdon=E2=80=99t refer to bribes by c=
utesy nicknames=E2=80=9D genres:
As well as routinely passing along information, [PDVSA commercial and suppl=
y unit manager Rene] Hecker talked to Morillo about the need to encrypt the=
ir conversations and about an offshore company he=E2=80=99d set up in Panam=
a. In one message, Hecker sent Morillo banking information for his father-i=
n-law, known as Gigante, writing in the subject line, =E2=80=9Cchamo elimin=
a estos archivos despues please=E2=80=9D (=E2=80=9Cdude delete these files =
later please=E2=80=9D). Before Christmas 2004, Gigante received two payment=
s totaling $400,000, Morillo=E2=80=99s bank statements show.
And:
A defendant in the case, who spoke on condition of anonymity, denies paying=
 bribes=E2=80=94his firm paid Helsinge =E2=80=9Cconsultancy fees=E2=80=9D=
=E2=80=94but says that exchanging information on rival bids and tenders was=
 =E2=80=9Cthe way of doing business=E2=80=9D in South America at the time.
Ah, yes, great, great.
But the other part of the Businessweek story=C2=A0is that this story of cor=
ruption and bribery =E2=80=94=C2=A0and Morillo=E2=80=99s instant messages a=
llegedly proving it =E2=80=94=C2=A0fell into the hands of David Boies, the =
famous American lawyer, who saw that Morillo and his clients had stolen bil=
lions of dollars from Venezuela and decided to try to get that money for hi=
mself:

Excited by the evidence in their possession, various combinations of Boies,=
 [Morillo=E2=80=99s rival Wilmer] Ruperti, Blondie (the private investigato=
r) and [investor Bill] Duker (the moneyman) met over the summer of 2017 in =
various offices and on Duker=E2=80=99s 230=E2=80=91foot sailboat,=C2=A0Syba=
ris, named for an ancient Greek city famous for its excess. =E2=80=A6
First they needed to persuade the Maduro administration to let them bring a=
 claim on PDVSA=E2=80=99s behalf. =E2=80=A6 Ruperti introduced Boies and Du=
ker to Nelson Martinez, Venezuela=E2=80=99s newly installed oil minister, a=
nd Reinaldo Mu=C3=B1oz Pedroza, the country=E2=80=99s attorney general. On =
July 12, 2017, the parties came to an agreement: Blondie, Duker and the law=
yers would get 66% of the proceeds, leaving 34% for PDVSA.=C2=A0

So they set up an entity =E2=80=94=C2=A0PDVSA US Litigation Trust =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0to sue Morillo and his clients in Florida federal court, and to pay a=
ny winnings two-thirds to the lawyers and one-third to PDVSA. They sued, an=
d the defendants=E2=80=99 first line of defense was, basically, =E2=80=9Clo=
ok, you say that we stole billions of dollars from PDVSA, but why do=C2=A0y=
ou=C2=A0get to sue?=C2=A0You=C2=A0aren=E2=80=99t PDVSA; you=E2=80=99re some=
 weird new trust. If we stole from PDVSA, let PDVSA sue us.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Back in court in Miami, before the proceedings could turn to the matter of =
whether Helsinge and its customers had committed any crimes, Boies needed t=
o demonstrate that the trust had standing=E2=80=94the legal right to bring =
a case. In most lawsuits, an injured party files a complaint and the two si=
des argue over its merits. Here you had an opaque New York vehicle claiming=
 to represent Venezuela=E2=80=99s state oil company, which itself was contr=
olled by a corrupt dictator subject to sanctions. Beyond that, it was uncle=
ar from the preliminary filings who controlled the trust and who stood to b=
enefit. In July 2018 the defendants filed a motion to have the case dismiss=
ed on the grounds that the trust was illegitimate.
This defense was helped by the fact that nobody from PDVSA could really com=
e to court to explain that the trust was legitimate, because (1) Venezuela =
was subject to increasingly strict US sanctions that made it hard for Boies=
 to work with PDVSA and=C2=A0(2) the Venezuelan government didn=E2=80=99t m=
ake it particularly easy either:

What followed was a kind of courtroom farce, as Boies Schiller Flexner=E2=
=80=99s increasingly desperate efforts to demonstrate the trust=E2=80=99s b=
ona fides fell apart under scrutiny. Defense lawyers sought to depose Venez=
uelan signatories to the litigation agreement among the various parties, bu=
t none could be pinned down. One had simply vanished. Another, Martinez, th=
e oil minister, had recently been=C2=A0arrested in Venezuela and charged wi=
th corruption. =E2=80=9CJailed? Did I hear jailed?=E2=80=9D the judge asked=
, trying to keep up. When PDVSA=E2=80=99s general counsel did finally commi=
t to going to the US to be deposed, two dozen attorneys booked flights and =
hotels, only for the witness to pull out at the last minute, apparently und=
er orders from Maduro himself.
The plaintiffs=E2=80=99 position was further undermined by how poorly news =
of the litigation was going down in South America. As part of the discovery=
 process, Boies Schiller Flexner was ordered to hand over the agreement let=
ter laying out the 66%-34% split. It was pilloried on Venezuelan state tele=
vision. On April 24, 2018, the National Assembly, home to what remains of t=
he country=E2=80=99s opposition, published a decree describing the trust as=
 =E2=80=9Ca mechanism to divert the funds and resources=E2=80=9D of Venezue=
la.

Ultimately this defense worked, and the judge dismissed Boies=E2=80=99s law=
suit. I love that a famous=C2=A0US lawyer learned of Swiss companies defrau=
ding a Venezuelan company out of billions of dollars, and his natural first=
 reaction was to go to a US federal court to get it to order those companie=
s to give him the money instead. =E2=80=9CIf a US lawyer notices anyone ste=
aling any money=C2=A0anywhere in the world, that money belongs to him, and =
a US court will enforce his rights to it=E2=80=9D is not=C2=A0100%=C2=A0wro=
ng as a description=C2=A0of US law, which explains a lot about the extrater=
ritorial application of US law, the hegemony of the dollar system, and the =
entrepreneurial American legal culture. But it is not 100% right either, an=
d it did not work out for Boies.
Anyway, elsewhere in euphemisms for bribes, here is the Economist  with a h=
elpful collection:
One approach is to talk about something other than money. Some officials, f=
or example, like to keep citizens well abreast of their food and drink pref=
erences. =E2=80=9CI really want to drink a Nescafe,=E2=80=9D declares an ai=
rport security guard six times as he frisks your correspondent in Burkina F=
aso. In Uganda traffic police find ways to mention their favourite soda. In=
 South Africa such requests are so common that bribes for driving offences =
are known as =E2=80=9Ccold drink money=E2=80=9D.
I guess if you=E2=80=99re a cop at a traffic stop you can=E2=80=99t really =
ask for a consultancy=C2=A0fee.

