o so again=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 and I will feel dumb and amazed if the people=
 who bought Bed Bath stock on Friday at $0.29 end up making a fortune on th=
e trade.


  [5] This is a little loose, and there are scenarios where some equity own=
er might put in more money in a bankruptcy-type situation in order to *keep=
 control of the company*. =E2=80=9CAn equity owner throws in more money and=
 comes out with zero stake in the company" is =E2=80=A6 less common.


  [6] No, no, it=E2=80=99s still trading; it was at about $0.19 or so at no=
on today. Really this should say =E2=80=9C=E2=80=A6 and (2) now is even mor=
e clearly going to be worthless,=E2=80=9D but all hope is not technically l=
ost.


  [7] Bloomberg reports: =E2=80=9C=E2=80=98The idea that you can continuall=
y support your company even in the face of constant dilution of your invest=
ors just isn=E2=80=99t a long-term, viable corporate-finance strategy,=E2=
=80=99 said James Gellert, CEO of ratings firm Rapid Ratings. =E2=80=98Bed =
Bath & Beyond had a seeming disregard for common equity holders.=E2=80=99=
