ourse =E2=80=94=C2=A0basically, after Hudson Bay and Bed Bath drove the sto=
ck price from above $3 to below $1 by pounding out about 311 million shares=
 to retail investors =E2=80=94=C2=A0Bed Bath and its brokers at B. Riley Se=
curities Inc. sold=C2=A0<em>another=C2=A0</em>311 million shares to retail =
investors, but at ever-declining prices, so they raised a lot less money. S=
till something, though.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It was not enough, though, and ultimately this=
 weekend Bed Bath &amp; Beyond filed for <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloom=
bergbusiness.com/click/31266131.261440/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9u=
ZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDQtMjMvYmVkLWJhdGgtYmV5b25kLXBsYW5zLXRvLXN3aWZ0bHk=
tbGlxdWlkYXRlLXNodXR0ZXItc3RvcmVzP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA0MjQyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV=
9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDQyNCZ1dG1fY=
2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa45c16a8" itemprop=3D"St=
oryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000;=
 text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-=
color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">
exactly the sort of bankruptcy</a> it was contemplating in January: Close a=
ll the stores, liquidate the inventory, hand whatever cash is left=C2=A0to =
the creditors. =E2=80=9CThe Debtors are committed to achieving the highest =
or otherwise best bid for some or all of the Debtors=E2=80=99 assets by mar=
keting their assets pursuant to the Bidding Procedures, and, if necessary, =
conducting an auction for any of their assets,=E2=80=9D the company says, b=
ut it has had like four months to find someone interested in buying the bus=
iness, and if no one has shown up yet no one is going to. And: =E2=80=9CThe=
 Debtors estimate that the aggregate net sales proceeds from all Sales will=
 be approximately $718 million,=E2=80=9D against=C2=A0about $1.8 billion of=
 debt to pay off.=C2=A0Nonetheless:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">While the commencement of a full c=
hain wind-down is necessitated by economic realities, Bed Bath &amp; Beyond=
 has and will continue to market their businesses as a going-concern, inclu=
ding the buybuy Baby business. Bed Bath &amp; Beyond has pulled off long sh=
ot transactions several times in the last six months, so nobody should thin=
k Bed Bath &amp; Beyond will not be able to do so again. To the contrary, B=
ed Bath &amp; Beyond and its professionals will make every effort to salvag=
e all or a portion of operations for the benefit of all stakeholders.</p></=
blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I said above that the few hundred million doll=
ars that Bed Bath raised by selling 622 million shares of stock=C2=A0<em>si=
nce it started preparing for bankruptcy </em>=E2=80=9Cwas not enough=E2=80=
=9D to solve its problems, but it=E2=80=99s actually a bit worse than that.=
 Bed Bath=E2=80=99s bankruptcy filing=C2=A0tells a story in which the compa=
ny got into a bad place due to a combination of pandemic/supply-chain issue=
s and its own management mistakes; in particular, its former chief executiv=
e officer pushed private-label brands instead of the well-known brands that=
 its customers wanted. Bed Bath realized its mistakes and began correcting =
them =E2=80=94=C2=A0that CEO =E2=80=9Cwas excused on June 29, 2022=E2=80=9D=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0but that takes money; =E2=80=9Cthe Company needed real runw=
ay to turn around its inventory and liquidity position.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But the story is=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>that i=
t then went out and raised several hundred million dollars to build up its =
inventory and make its business more attractive. No, the story is that it w=
ent out and raised several hundred million dollars to hand directly=C2=A0to=
 its creditors:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Unfortunately, under the terms of the Second A=
mended Credit Agreement, the Debtors were required to use the net proceeds =
from the initial closing of the [Hudson Bay] Offering, along with the FILO =
Upsize, to repay outstanding revolving loans under the Debtors=E2=80=99 Pre=
petition ABL=C2=A0Facility, including repayment of the nearly $200 million =
overadvance. At this point the Company=E2=80=99s sales had dropped 60% on a=
 comparable store basis, resulting in substantial ongoing losses from opera=
tion; therefore, the remaining Offering proceeds went to cover operational =
losses rather than to restoring inventory levels. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The net proceeds from the B. Riley ATM Program=
 were used to prepay outstanding revolving loans under the Debtors=E2=80=99=
 Prepetition ABL Facility and cash collateralize outstanding letters of cre=
dit, resulting in new credit under the Debtors=E2=80=99 Prepetition ABL Fac=
ility. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Debtors=E2=80=99 cash burn continued while=
 sales further declined due to lack of incoming merchandise, thus, preventi=
ng the Debtors from implementing their anticipated long-term operational re=
structuring while satisfying their restrictive debt obligations.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That is, Bed Bath had an asset-based lending f=
acility (its most senior debt) and a <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomberg=
business.com/click/31266131.261440/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubGV4b2xvZ3kuY29tL2xpYnJh=
cnkvZGV0YWlsLmFzcHg_Zz1iZDBkYWEwOS1hYzg4LTQ3OTMtOGJjNy1jOTY5YmFmN2Q3NDk/607=
f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc2a518cb" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemsco=
pe" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !impor=
tant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom=
-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> first-in-last-out term loan</a> (e=
ffectively its second-most-senior debt); <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloom=
bergbusiness.com/click/31266131.261440/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9peD9kb2M9=
L0FyY2hpdmVzL2VkZ2FyL2RhdGEvODg2MTU4LzAwMDA4ODYxNTgyMzAwMDAyNi9iYmJ5LTIwMjI=
xMTI2Lmh0bQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cC0039fb2b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" items=
cope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorati=
on: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000=
; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> as of November 2022=
</a>, it had borrowed $550 million on the ABL (plus $186.2 million of lette=
rs of credit) and $375 million on the FILO. As of Sunday there was $80.3 mi=
llion outstanding on the ABL (plus $102.6 million of letters of credit) and=
 $547.1 million outstanding on the FILO.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D=
"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bo=
rder-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: =
none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-=
block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a> Since this all began, Bed Bath has raised a bit more than $400 million=
 from shareholders and handed about $300 million of it directly to its lend=
ers, while the business collapsed and it had no money to fix things. Now it=
 will hand the rest of its money over to the lenders.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t know what to say? All of this =
was quite well disclosed. Back when Bed Bath did the Hudson Bay deal in Jan=
uary, it <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31266131.=
261440/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzg4NjE1OC8wMDAx=
MTkzMTI1MjMwMzAzNTYvZDQwNjM2OGQ0MjRiNS5odG0jc3VwcHJvbTQwNjM2OF82/607f07ceef=
4b8524a319a23cBde03535f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" tar=
get=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; b=
order-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style:=
 solid; background-color: #ccc;"> said in the prospectus</a> that it intend=
ed to use all the money it raised to repay debt, and that if it didn=E2=80=
=99t raise a billion dollars in that deal (it did not) then it =E2=80=9Cwou=
ld not have the financial resources to satisfy its payment obligations,=E2=
=80=9D it=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cwill likely file for bankruptcy protection,=E2=80=
=9D =E2=80=9Cits assets will likely be liquidated=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cour=
 equity holders would likely not receive any recovery at all in a bankruptc=
y scenario.=E2=80=9D All of the legal documents were pretty clear that Bed =
Bath was raising money by selling stock to retail investors, that it was ha=
nding that money directly to its creditors, that the money probably wouldn=
=E2=80=99t be enough, that Bed Bath was probably going bankrupt, and that w=
hen it did the stock that it had just sold to those retail investors would =
be worthless. And things have worked out exactly as promised. No one can be=
 surprised!</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And yet it is one of the most astonishing corp=
orate finance transactions I=E2=80=99ve ever seen?<a class=3D"footnote-inde=
x" href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !imp=
ortant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bott=
om-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; displa=
y: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a>=C2=A0The basic rules of bankruptcy are:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">When a company is bankrupt, the share=
holders get zero dollars back, and the creditors get whatever=E2=80=99s lef=
t.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The shareholders don=E2=80=99t =
get=C2=A0<em>less=C2=A0</em>than zero. They don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0<em>put more=
 money in</em>.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-5" style=3D"co=
lor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; b=
order-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; backgrou=
nd-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a>
</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here, I mean, Bed Bath was kind of like =E2=80=
=9Chey everyone, we went bust, sorry, but our lenders are such nice people =
and they could really use a break, we=E2=80=99re gonna pass the hat and it =
would be great if you could throw in a few hundred million dollars to make =
them feel better.=E2=80=9D And the retail shareholders did! With more or le=
ss complete disclosure, they bought 622 million shares of a stock that (1) =
was pretty clearly going to be worthless and (2) now is worthless,<a class=
=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-6" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !=
important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[6]</span>
</a>=C2=A0so that Bed Bath could have more money to give to its lenders whe=
n it inevitably liquidated.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I have over the past few years <a href=3D"http=
s://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31266131.261440/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY=
mxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDYtMDIvYW1jLWJyaW5ncy1vdXQt=
dGhlLXBvcGNvcm4_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDQyNDIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ=
1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwNDI0JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leX=
N0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB58081b5d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  been impressed</a> by =
AMC Entertainment Holdings Inc.=E2=80=99s commitment to the meme-stock bit.=
 In particular, AMC=E2=80=99s management was early and aggressive in realiz=
ing that being a meme stock could be a tool of corporate finance, that when=
 people on Reddit are bidding up your stock for no clear reason, the correc=
t reaction is not to chuckle in disbelief but to=C2=A0<em>sell them stock</=
em>. But AMC at least has a story; AMC is using its meme investors=E2=80=99=
 money to pay down debt, sure, but also to keep its theaters open and <a hr=
ef=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31266131.261440/aHR0cHM=
6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDMtMTUvYW1jLWJvdW=
dodC1hLWdvbGQtbWluZT9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNDI0MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtY=
WlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzA0MjQmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1v=
bmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBba2df642" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" items=
cope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorati=
on: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000=
; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  buy a gold mine</a=
>.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">No,=C2=A0<em>this=C2=A0</em>is the peak of mem=
e stocks. Bed Bath &amp; Beyond sold 50 million shares a week for three mon=
ths with, as far as I can tell,=C2=A0<em>no=C2=A0</em>story,=C2=A0<em>no=C2=
=A0</em>plan, nothing but =E2=80=9Ca troubled financial situation and=C2=A0=
nostalgia value.=E2=80=9D<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-7" s=
tyle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wid=
th: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important=
; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[7]</span>
</a>=C2=A0Bed Bath saw that its retail shareholders wanted to throw their m=
oney away, and that its sophisticated lenders wanted to get their money bac=
k, and realized that there was a trade to be done that would make everyone,=
 temporarily, happy. So it did the trade. It=E2=80=99s amazing. The lawsuit=
s are gonna be great.</p>
