<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Dual-class stock</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Most investors would prefer not to have dual-c=
lass stock. If a company has two classes of common stock, one of which has =
a lot of votes and is held by the founders and the other one of which has f=
ewer votes and is sold to the public, then that=E2=80=99s bad, for you, as =
a big public shareholder. If you=E2=80=99re buying 5% of a company you=E2=
=80=99d like to get 5% of the votes, so that if you get dissatisfied with m=
anagement you can push for change and they=E2=80=99ll have to listen to you=
.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But it can be a little hard to=C2=A0<em>insist=
=C2=A0</em>on this preference. Most of the time, if things work out well or=
 even adequately, your voting rights just won=E2=80=99t matter very much. I=
f some hot tech company is looking to go public with dual-class stock so th=
at its visionary founder can keep control forever, and you like the visiona=
ry founder, you will want to own the stock even with no voting rights, and =
if you insist on voting rights, the visionary founder can say =E2=80=9Cwell=
 I don=E2=80=99t need your money anyway, lots of other people want to inves=
t.=E2=80=9D There is a collective action problem: Most investors would=C2=
=A0<em>like=C2=A0</em>voting rights, but it=E2=80=99s not at the top of the=
ir list, so anyone who refuses to buy dual-class stock will end up missing =
out on a lot of hot deals.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This means that, if you are a visionary founde=
r looking to go public, there=E2=80=99s not much downside to having dual-cl=
ass stock. =E2=80=9CInvestors won=E2=80=99t like it,=E2=80=9D your bankers =
will tell you, and you will ask =E2=80=9Cwell how much less will they pay f=
or the stock if it=E2=80=99s dual-class,=E2=80=9D and the bankers will be f=
orced to reply =E2=80=9Cwell they=E2=80=99ll pay the same price but they=E2=
=80=99ll grumble about it to the press.=E2=80=9D Who cares? If there is no =
visible=C2=A0<em>economic=C2=A0</em>penalty for having dual-class stock, lo=
ts of founders will want it.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is, however, at least one way for invest=
ors to act collectively to address this problem. Sort of. Companies, and fo=
unders, want to be in stock=C2=A0<em>indexes</em>, because there is a lot o=
f money there: Trillions of dollars are managed in indexed strategies, and =
trillions more are in funds that are benchmarked to indexes and tend to inv=
est in companies in indexes. So there=C2=A0<em>is=C2=A0</em>an economic pen=
alty for companies that are not eligible for the indexes. And index eligibi=
lity rules are set by index providers like S&amp;P Dow Jones Indices and FT=
SE Russell. Those companies can change their rules if they want. Those comp=
anies=E2=80=99=C2=A0<em>clients=C2=A0</em>are investment managers who use t=
heir indexes. And the index eligibility rules are, to some extent, a matter=
 of <em>customer service=C2=A0</em>and=C2=A0<em>marketing:=C2=A0</em>Index =
rules are not just about the abstract pursuit of truth (=E2=80=9CWhat does =
it mean to be a large-cap company in Europe, the Middle East and Africa? Ho=
w do we make sure all of those companies are in our index?=E2=80=9D), but a=
lso about providing a useful product for your customers (=E2=80=9CWhat list=
 of large-cap EMEA companies do large-cap EMEA index fund managers feel lik=
e they should invest in?=E2=80=9D).</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so if all the investment managers hate dua=
l-class stock, they can quietly call up the index providers and say =E2=80=
=9Chey it would be helpful for us if you ban dual-class stocks from the ind=
ex, because then none of us could buy them and our collective action proble=
m would be solved.=E2=80=9D</p>
