arget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  S&amp;P Dow Jones</a> =E2=80=94=C2=A0c=
hanged their rules to exclude or limit dual-class stocks from many of their=
 indexes. The investors had solved their collective action problem; they ha=
d found a way to impose economic penalties on companies with dual-class sto=
ck.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It didn=E2=80=99t work. Companies kept going p=
ublic with dual-class stock. They didn=E2=80=99t care=C2=A0<em>that=C2=A0</=
em>much about missing out on the indexes; their founders were willing to pa=
y the economic price to keep control. (In particular, companies don=E2=80=
=99t generally get added to the S&amp;P 500=C2=A0<em>the day they go public=
</em>; a lot of index demand is not for shares in the IPO but later on, mea=
ning that it doesn=E2=80=99t directly affect the IPO price.) This means tha=
t the investors=E2=80=99 solution ended up being=C2=A0<em>bad=C2=A0</em>for=
 them: They credibly committed to not buying dual-class stock of hot compan=
ies, hot companies kept going public with dual-class stock, index funds cou=
ldn=E2=80=99t buy those stocks, and they were sad.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The solution was to give up. Last week <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31266131.261440/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuc3BnbG9iYWwuY29tL3NwZGppL2VuL2RvY3VtZW50cy9pbmRleG5ld3MvYW5ub3VuY2Vt=
ZW50cy8yMDIzMDQxNy0xNDYzNTQzLzE0NjM1NDNfcHJhcHJpbDIwMjMxNTAwc2hhcmVjbGFzc2N=
vbnN1bHRyZXN1bHRzLnBkZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf624c2b5" itemprop=3D"Stor=
yLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; t=
ext-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-co=
lor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> S&amp;P=
 Dow Jones announced</a> that dual-class stocks are fine again: =E2=80=9CEf=
fective April 17, 2023, all companies with multiple share class structures =
will be considered eligible candidates for addition to the S&amp;P Composit=
e 1500 and its component indices,=E2=80=9D including the S&amp;P 500. Here=
=E2=80=99s a <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31266=
131.261440/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZGF2aXNwb2xrLmNvbS9pbnNpZ2h0cy9jbGllbnQtdXBkYXRl=
L3NwLWRvdy1qb25lcy1yZXZpc2l0cy1tdWx0aWNsYXNzLXNoYXJlcw/607f07ceef4b8524a319=
a23cB503fa1c5" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bl=
ank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; ba=
ckground-color: #ccc;"> Davis Polk &amp; Wardwell LLP client memo</a> from =
last week:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In response to Snap Inc.=E2=80=99s IPO in whic=
h only non-voting shares were offered to the public, the Council of Institu=
tional Investors and others had lobbied the major index providers to bar no=
n-voting shares from their indices, arguing that absent this change, passiv=
e investors such as index funds would be forced to invest in non-voting sha=
res that erode public company governance. As a result, since July 31, 2017,=
 S&amp;P Dow Jones has excluded companies with multiple share classes from =
the indices comprising the S&amp;P Composite 1500.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The decision to revisit index eligibility crit=
eria comes after a consultation process that S&amp;P Dow Jones ran with mar=
ket participants from October to December 2022.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In 2017, investors noisily=C2=A0complained tha=
t they were being forced to buy dual-class stocks, so S&amp;P kicked the du=
al-class stocks out of the indexes. In 2022, investors noisily complained t=
hat they were being forced=C2=A0<em>not </em>to buy dual-class stocks, so S=
&amp;P let them back in.</p>
