<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I loved Liam Vaughan=E2=80=99s and Lucia Kassa=
i=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/312661=
31.261440/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2ZlYXR1cmVzLzIwMjMtMDQtM=
jAvdmVuZXp1ZWxhLW9pbC1pbmR1c3RyeS1sb3N0LWJpbGxpb25zLWluLWJpZC1yaWdnaW5nLXNj=
YW5kYWw_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDQyNDIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc29=
1cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwNDI0JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/6=
07f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBafe48ed6" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"items=
cope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !imp=
ortant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bott=
om-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  Bloomberg Businessweek story</a=
> last week about corruption in Venezuelan oil auctions, in part because it=
 is two almost entirely separate stories of corruption. For starters, there=
 are the Venezuelan oil auctions. Venezuela=E2=80=99s state oil company, Pe=
tr=C3=B3leos de Venezuela SA, would sell various oil products in auctions, =
and big oil trading firms would hire=C2=A0a consulting firm named Helsinge,=
 run by a guy=C2=A0named Francisco Morillo, to help them win the auctions. =
The way he allegedly helped them win was (1) he bribed PDVSA insiders to te=
ll him about the other bids, (2) he shared those bids with his clients, (3)=
 the clients topped those bids by a penny and (4) they paid him enough to c=
over the bribes with some profit for himself:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In one series of chats from March 14, 2006, Mo=
rillo, using the screen name George White, guided three prominent commodity=
 traders=E2=80=94Maarraoui at Vitol, Gustavo Gabaldon at Glencore and Maxim=
iliano Poveda at Trafigura=E2=80=94through auctions for fuel oil and a prod=
uct called vacuum gas oil, which is used to make gasoline. At 9:51 a.m., ni=
ne minutes before the offers were due, Morillo shared details of the bids P=
DVSA had received for the vacuum gas oil=E2=80=94information PDVSA says is =
supposed to be confidential. Five minutes later he informed the three trade=
rs, via separate chats, of a late bid for the fuel oil.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The traders didn=E2=80=99t enter every auction=
, but when they did bid, the information Morillo had provided let them know=
 at what price to do so. On March 20, 2006, after learning about offers fro=
m BP Plc and two other companies, Maarraoui placed a bid to buy gas oil at =
0.8=C2=A2 per gallon more than the next-highest bidder. Two days later, Pov=
eda won a liquefied petroleum gas auction after being told about two rival =
offers and besting them by a cent.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">These conversations, a handful among thousands=
, demonstrate how valuable Helsinge=E2=80=99s service was to its customers=
=E2=80=94and how potentially devastating it was to the Venezuelan people. I=
f Morillo=E2=80=99s clients had been forced to enter the market blind, they=
 likely would have placed some bids at $5 or $10 per metric ton higher than=
 they needed to, as the chats show their competitors did. Instead the trade=
rs were able to win auctions they entered by a dollar or less, saving as mu=
ch as $1.5 million on a typical 150,000-ton cargo. According to the Boies c=
omplaint, they=E2=80=99d pay Helsinge about $300,000 on a shipment of that =
size. PDVSA declined to provide data to Businessweek on the outcome of its =
auctions, or to comment for this story, but given that the company conducte=
d dozens of auctions each month as buyer and seller, and that Helsinge was =
in business for 15 years, it=E2=80=99s conceivable Venezuela lost out on se=
veral billion this way.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also, if you keep doing this, eventually you=
=E2=80=99re going to drive everyone=C2=A0<em>else=C2=A0</em>out of the auct=
ions, further depressing prices:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Traders from two oil companies tol=
d Businessweek that they=E2=80=99d stopped participating in PDVSA=E2=80=99s=
 auctions because they were sick of losing to the same players. =E2=80=9CPu=
tting together an offer takes time. You need to figure out the economics, f=
reight, insurance, the hedge, then submit to your compliance, get signature=
s from God knows who before you=E2=80=99re able to submit a number,=E2=80=
=9D says one of the individuals, who asked not to be identified. =E2=80=9CA=
fter a while we just gave up. It became clear to us that something funny wa=
s happening.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This part of the story includes some classics =
of the =E2=80=9Cdon=E2=80=99t put it in writing=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cdon=
=E2=80=99t refer to bribes by cutesy nicknames=E2=80=9D genres:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As well as routinely passing along=
 information, [PDVSA commercial and supply unit manager Rene] Hecker talked=
 to Morillo about the need to encrypt their conversations and about an offs=
hore company he=E2=80=99d set up in Panama. In one message, Hecker sent Mor=
illo banking information for his father-in-law, known as Gigante, writing i=
n the subject line, =E2=80=9C<em>chamo elimina estos archivos despues pleas=
e</em>=E2=80=9D (=E2=80=9Cdude delete these files later please=E2=80=9D). B=
efore Christmas 2004, Gigante received two payments totaling $400,000, Mori=
llo=E2=80=99s bank statements show.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A defendant in the case, who spoke=
 on condition of anonymity, denies paying bribes=E2=80=94his firm paid Hels=
inge =E2=80=9Cconsultancy fees=E2=80=9D=E2=80=94but says that exchanging in=
formation on rival bids and tenders was =E2=80=9Cthe way of doing business=
=E2=80=9D in South America at the time.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Ah, yes, great, great.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But the other part of the Businessweek story=
=C2=A0is that this story of corruption and bribery =E2=80=94=C2=A0and Moril=
lo=E2=80=99s instant messages allegedly proving it =E2=80=94=C2=A0fell into=
 the hands of David Boies, the famous American lawyer, who saw that Morillo=
 and his clients had stolen billions of dollars from Venezuela and decided =
to try to get that money for himself:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Excited by the evidence in their possession, v=
arious combinations of Boies, [Morillo=E2=80=99s rival Wilmer] Ruperti, Blo=
ndie (the private investigator) and [investor Bill] Duker (the moneyman) me=
t over the summer of 2017 in various offices and on Duker=E2=80=99s 230=E2=
=80=91foot sailboat,=C2=A0<em>Sybaris</em>, named for an ancient Greek city=
 famous for its excess. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">First they needed to persuade the Maduro admin=
istration to let them bring a claim on PDVSA=E2=80=99s behalf. =E2=80=A6 Ru=
perti introduced Boies and Duker to Nelson Martinez, Venezuela=E2=80=99s ne=
wly installed oil minister, and Reinaldo Mu=C3=B1oz Pedroza, the country=E2=
=80=99s attorney general. On July 12, 2017, the parties came to an agreemen=
t: Blondie, Duker and the lawyers would get 66% of the proceeds, leaving 34=
% for PDVSA.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So they set up an entity =E2=80=94=C2=A0PDVSA =
US Litigation Trust =E2=80=94=C2=A0to sue Morillo and his clients in Florid=
a federal court, and to pay any winnings two-thirds to the lawyers and one-=
third to PDVSA. They sued, and the defendants=E2=80=99 first line of defens=
e was, basically, =E2=80=9Clook, you say that we stole billions of dollars =
from PDVSA, but why do=C2=A0<em>you=C2=A0</em>get to sue?=C2=A0<em>You=C2=
=A0</em>aren=E2=80=99t PDVSA; you=E2=80=99re some weird new trust. If we st=
ole from PDVSA, let PDVSA sue us.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Back in court in Miami, before the=
 proceedings could turn to the matter of whether Helsinge and its customers=
 had committed any crimes, Boies needed to demonstrate that the trust had s=
tanding=E2=80=94the legal right to bring a case. In most lawsuits, an injur=
ed party files a complaint and the two sides argue over its merits. Here yo=
u had an opaque New York vehicle claiming to represent Venezuela=E2=80=99s =
state oil company, which itself was controlled by a corrupt dictator subjec=
t to sanctions. Beyond that, it was unclear from the preliminary filings wh=
o controlled the trust and who stood to benefit. In July 2018 the defendant=
s filed a motion to have the case dismissed on the grounds that the trust w=
as illegitimate.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This defense was helped by the fact that nobod=
y from PDVSA could really come to court to explain that the trust was legit=
imate, because (1) Venezuela was subject to increasingly strict US sanction=
s that made it hard for Boies to work with PDVSA and=C2=A0(2) the Venezuela=
n government didn=E2=80=99t make it particularly easy either:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What followed was a kind of courtroom farce, a=
s Boies Schiller Flexner=E2=80=99s increasingly desperate efforts to demons=
trate the trust=E2=80=99s bona fides fell apart under scrutiny. Defense law=
yers sought to depose Venezuelan signatories to the litigation agreement am=
ong the various parties, but none could be pinned down. One had simply vani=
shed. Another, Martinez, the oil minister, had recently been=C2=A0arrested =
in Venezuela and charged with corruption. =E2=80=9CJailed? Did I hear jaile=
d?=E2=80=9D the judge asked, trying to keep up. When PDVSA=E2=80=99s genera=
l counsel did finally commit to going to the US to be deposed, two dozen at=
torneys booked flights and hotels, only for the witness to pull out at the =
last minute, apparently under orders from Maduro himself.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The plaintiffs=E2=80=99 position was further u=
ndermined by how poorly news of the litigation was going down in South Amer=
ica. As part of the discovery process, Boies Schiller Flexner was ordered t=
o hand over the agreement letter laying out the 66%-34% split. It was pillo=
ried on Venezuelan state television. On April 24, 2018, the National Assemb=
ly, home to what remains of the country=E2=80=99s opposition, published a d=
ecree describing the trust as =E2=80=9Ca mechanism to divert the funds and =
resources=E2=80=9D of Venezuela.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Ultimately this defense worked, and the judge =
dismissed Boies=E2=80=99s lawsuit. I love that a famous=C2=A0US lawyer lear=
ned of Swiss companies defrauding a Venezuelan company out of billions of d=
ollars, and his natural first reaction was to go to a US federal court to g=
et it to order those companies to give him the money instead. =E2=80=9CIf a=
 US lawyer notices anyone stealing any money=C2=A0anywhere in the world, th=
at money belongs to him, and a US court will enforce his rights to it=E2=80=
=9D is not=C2=A0<em>100%=C2=A0</em>wrong as a description=C2=A0of US law, w=
hich explains a lot about the extraterritorial application of US law, the h=
egemony of the dollar system, and the entrepreneurial American legal cultur=
e. But it is not 100% right either, and it did not work out for Boies.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway, elsewhere in euphemisms for bribes, he=
re is the Economist <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/clic=
k/31266131.261440/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZWNvbm9taXN0LmNvbS9taWRkbGUtZWFzdC1hbmQtY=
WZyaWNhLzIwMjMvMDQvMjAvaG93LXRvLWFzay1mb3ItYS1icmliZS13aXRob3V0LWFza2luZy1m=
b3ItYS1icmliZQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3cb59f2a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" it=
emscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decor=
ation: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000=
000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> with a helpful c=
ollection</a>:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One approach is to talk about some=
thing other than money. Some officials, for example, like to keep citizens =
well abreast of their food and drink preferences. =E2=80=9CI really want to=
 drink a Nescafe,=E2=80=9D declares an airport security guard six times as =
he frisks your correspondent in Burkina Faso. In Uganda traffic police find=
 ways to mention their favourite soda. In South Africa such requests are so=
 common that bribes for driving offences are known as =E2=80=9Ccold drink m=
oney=E2=80=9D.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I guess if you=E2=80=99re a cop at a traffic s=
top you can=E2=80=99t really ask for a consultancy=C2=A0fee.</p>
